{"parse":{"title":"physician","pageid":67777,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|phisician|phisitian|physitian||obsolete}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|fisicien|}}, from {{der|en|fro|fisicïen||physician}} (modern {{cog|fr|physicien||physicist}}), from {{m|fro|fisique||art of healing}}, from {{der|en|la|physica||natural science}}, from {{der|en|grc|[[φυσική]] [[ἐπιστήμη]]||knowledge of nature}}, from {{m|grc|φυσικός||pertaining to nature}}. Displaced native {{ncog|enm|leche|læche, leche}}, archaic {{m+|en|leech|id=physician|gloss=physician}}. Morphologically {{af|en|physic|-ian}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/fəˈzɪʃən/|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/fɪˈzɪʃn̩/|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|En-us-physician.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{hyph|en|phy|si|cian}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A practitioner of [[physic]], i.e. a specialist in internal medicine, especially as opposed to a [[surgeon]]; a practitioner who treats with [[medication]] rather than with [[surgery]].\n#* {{RQ:Chambers Younger Set|II|passage=His forefathers had been, as a rule, professional men&mdash;'''physicians''' and lawyers; his grandfather died under the walls of Chapultepec Castle while twisting a tourniquet for a cursing dragoon; an uncle remained indefinitely at Malvern Hill;{{nb...}}.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date= 4 August 2010|title= The Ethics of Enhanced Interrogations and Torture: A Reappraisal of the Argument|author= Leonard S. Rubenstein, JD; Stephen N. Xenakis, MD|publisher= w:American Medical Association|work=JAMA|volume=304|issue=5|pages=569–570|url= https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/186317 |doi=10.1001/jama.2010.1057 |passage=  In 2009, the Obama Administration released guidelines on enhanced interrogation written in 2003 and 2004 by the CIA Office of Medical Services. <sup>(OMS).1-3(appendix F)</sup> The OMS guidelines, even in redacted form, and opinions from the US Department of Justice's (DOJ’s) Office of Legal Counsel show that CIA '''physicians''', psychologists, and other health care personnel had important roles in enhanced interrogation.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Jonathan Reiner|title=If you think that glass of wine is good for you, it’s time to reconsider|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/01/22/opinions/alcohol-heart-health-reiner|date=2022-01-22|passage=The ancient Greek '''physician''' Hippocrates promoted wine for various purposes, including reducing fevers and dressing wounds.}}\n# {{senseid|en|Q39631}} A [[medical]] [[doctor]] trained in [[human]] [[medicine]].\n#: {{syn|en|doctor<id:Q39631>|Thesaurus:physician}}\n#: {{hyper|en|person#Noun}}\n#: {{hypo|en|resident doctor<id:Q6313534><qq:UK>|resident<id:Q88655413>|attending#Noun|;|general practitioner|internist|surgeon|neurologist|radiologist|pathologist|ophthalmologist|otologist}}\n#* {{RQ:Stevenson Treasure Island|text=The doctor had to go to London for a '''physician''' to take charge of his practice{{nb...}}.}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* In the [[United Kingdom]] and {{w|Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth}} countries, a physician holds a postgraduate degree such as ''Master of General Medicine'' or fellowship certificate such as [[MRCP]] or [[FRCP]] from the {{w|Royal College of Physicians}} in UK, or the {{w|Royal Australasian College of Physicians}} in Australia and New Zealand. Contrarily, in the United States, the term is frequently regulated by state laws, and in all states includes those with the {{w|Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine}} (D.O.) degree (not to be confused with [[osteopath]]s), the {{w|Doctor of Medicine}} (M.D.) degree, and in some states those with the D.C. (Doctor of Chiropractic) degree (who are neither medical doctors nor part of {{w|Allied health professions|allied health}}).\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col2|en|physician, heal thyself| emergency physician|family physician|non-physician|physician assistant|physician extender|physician associate|physician finger|geophysician|interphysician|intraphysician|nonphysician|physiciancy|physicianed|physicianess|physicianless|physicianlike|physicianly|physicianship}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col3|en|physic|physicist|physical|physics}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|medical doctor}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|dokter}}\n* Akan: {{t|ak|dɔkota|n}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|mjek|m}}, {{t+|sq|mjeke|f}}, {{t+|sq|doktor|m}}, {{t+|sq|doktoreshë|f}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|ሐኪም|m}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|طَبِيب|m}}, {{t|ar|طَبِيبة|f}}, {{t|ar|دُكْتُور|m|tr=doktōr, duktōr}}, {{t+|ar|حَكِيم|m}}, {{t|ar|حَكِيمَة|f}}, {{t|ar|مُتَطبِّب|m}}\n*: Chadian Arabic: {{t|shu|دكتور|m|tr=daktōr}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|دكتور|m|tr=doktōr}}, {{t|arz|حكيم|m|tr=ḥakīm}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|دكتور|m|tr=duktōr}}, {{t|acw|طبيب|m|tr=ṭabīb}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|طبيب|tr=ṭbīb}}\n*: North Levantine Arabic: {{t|ajp|حَكِيم|tr=ḥakīm}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܐܵܣܝܵܐ|m|tr=asya}}, {{t|aii|ܕܘܼܟ݂ܛܘܼܪ|n|tr=duḳṭur}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n*: Classical Syriac: {{t|syc|ܐܣܝܐ|m|tr=ʾāsyā}}\n*: Jewish Aramaic: {{t|arc|אָסְיָא|m|tr=ʾāsyā}}, {{t|arc|אַסְיָא|m|tr=ʾasyā}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|բժիշկ}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|ডাক্তৰ}}, {{t|as|বেজ}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|médicu|m}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|həkim}}, {{t+|az|doktor}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|sendagile}}, {{t+|eu|osagile}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|ура́ч|m|f}}, {{t|be|до́ктар|m|f}}, {{t|be|ле́кар|m}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|ডাক্তার}}, {{t+|bn|তবীব}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|doktor|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|до́ктор|m}}, {{t+|bg|ле́кар|m}}, {{t+|bg|хеки́мин|m}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ဆရာဝန်}}\n* Buryat: {{t|bua|эмшэн}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|metge|m}}\n* Cebuano: {{t|ceb|mantatambal}}\n* Chechen: {{t|ce|лор}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎦᎾᎦᏘ}}\n* Chichewa: {{t|ny|dokotala}}, {{t|ny|dotolo}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|醫生|tr=ji1 sang1}}\n*: Dungan: {{t|dng|дэфу}}, {{t|dng|щянсын}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{t|cdo|醫生|tr=ĭ-sĕng}}\n*: Hakka: {{t|hak|醫生|tr=yî-sên}}, {{t|hak|先生|tr=sîn-sâng}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|醫生|tr=i-seng}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|先生|tr=sian-seⁿ, sian-siⁿ}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|醫生|tr=yīshēng}}, {{t+|cmn|大夫|tr=dàifu}}, {{t+|cmn|醫師|tr=yīshī}}\n*: Wu: {{t|wuu|醫生}}\n* Chukchi: {{t|ckt|инэнмэлевыльын|tr=inėnmėlevylʹyn}}\n* Comorian:\n*: Ngazidja Comorian: {{t|zdj|twaɓiɓu|c5|c6}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|doktour|m}}, {{t|kw|medhek|m}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|lékař|m}}, {{t+|cs|lékařka|f}}, {{t+|cs|doktor|m}}, {{t+|cs|doktorka|f}}\n* Dalmatian: {{t|dlm|dotuar|m}}, {{t|dlm|medco|m}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|læge|c}}, {{t|da|doktor|c}}\n* Dusun:\n*: Central Dusun: {{t|dtp|dokutul}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|dokter|m}}, {{t+|nl|arts|m|f}}, {{t+|nl|geneesheer|m}} {{q|formal}}\n* Dzongkha: {{t|dz|དྲུང་འཚོ}}\n* Egyptian: {{t-egy|zjnw|h=zin:nw-A1}}\n* Emilian: {{t|egl|dutåur|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|kuracisto}}, {{t|eo|virkuracisto|m}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|arst}}, {{t|et|doktor}}\n* Evenki: {{t|evn|аичимни}}\n* Ewe: {{t|ee|ɖɔkta}}, {{t|ee|atikewɔla}}\n* Farefare: {{t|gur|dɔɣɔta}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|lækni|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|lääkäri}}, {{t+|fi|tohtori}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|médecin|m|f}}, {{t+|fr|docteur|m}}, {{t+|fr|docteure|f}}, {{t+|fr|doctoresse|f}}, {{t+|fr|doctoresse|f}}\n*: Old French: {{t|fro|fisician|m}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|dotôr|m}}, {{t|fur|miedi|m}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|doutor|m}}, {{t+|gl|médico|m}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ექიმი}}, {{t|ka|მედიკოსი}}, {{t|ka|მკურნალი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Arzt|m}}, {{t+|de|Ärztin|f}}, {{t+|de|Mediziner|m}}, {{t+|de|Medizinerin|f}}, {{t+|de|Doktor|m}}, {{t+|de|Doktorin|f}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐌻𐌴𐌺𐌴𐌹𐍃|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ιατρός|m|f}}, {{t+|el|γιατρός|m|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἰατρός|m}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|nakorsaq}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|kauka}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|רוֹפֵא|m|tr=rofé}}, {{t|he|רוֹפְאָה|f|tr=rof'á}}, {{t+|he|דוֹקטוֹר|m|tr=dóktor}} {{q|colloquial, while addressing a doctor}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|डाक्टर|m}}, {{t|hi|डॉक्टर|m}}, {{t+|hi|वैद्य|m}}, {{t+|hi|चिकित्सक|m}}, {{t+|hi|हकीम|m}}, {{t+|hi|तबीब|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|orvos|m}}, {{t+|hu|doktor|m}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|læknir|m}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|mediko}}, {{t+|io|medikulo}} {{qualifier|male}}, {{t+|io|medikino}} {{qualifier|female}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|dokter}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|doktori}}, {{t|izh|dohteri}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|medico}}, {{t|ia|doctor}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|lia|m}}, {{t+|ga|dochtúir|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|medico|m}}, {{t+|it|dottore|m}}, {{t|it|dottore in medicina|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|医者|tr=いしゃ, isha}}, {{t+|ja|医師|tr=いし, ishi}}, {{t+|ja|先生|tr=せんせい, sensei}} {{q|when addressing}}\n* Kalmyk: {{t|xal|эмч}}\n* Kamba: {{t|kam|ndakitali}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|дәрігер}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|ពេទ្យ}}, {{t+|km|ហ្ម}}, {{t|km|ពេទ្យហ្ម}}, {{t+|km|វេជ្ជ}}\n* Kikuyu: {{t|ki|ndagĩtarĩ|c1}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|의사(醫師)}}, {{t+|ko|의자(醫者)}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t|ckb|پزشک}}, {{t|ckb|دکتۆر}}, {{t|ckb|پزیشک|tr=pizîşk}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|bijîşk}}, {{t+|kmr|doktor}}, {{t+|kmr|tixtor}}, {{t+|kmr|nojdar}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|дарыгер}}\n* Ladino: {{t|lad|doktor}}, {{t|lad|mediko}}, {{t|lad|kechim}}\n* Lao: {{t+|lo|ໝໍ}}, {{t|lo|ແພດ}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|medicus|m}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|ārsts|m}}, {{t|lv|ārste|f}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|dokotolo}}, {{t|ln|monganga}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|daktaras|m}}, {{t|lt|daktarė|f}}, {{t+|lt|gydytojas|m}}, {{t|lt|gydytoja|f}}\n* Lombard: {{t|lmo|dotór|m}}\n* Low German:\n*: German Low German: {{t+|nds-de|Dokter|m}}, {{t|nds-de|Dokterin|f}}, {{t|nds-de|Doktersch|f}}, {{t|nds-de|Doktersche|f}}\n* Lü: {{t|khb|ᦖᦸ}}\n* Luhya: {{t|luy|dakatari}}, {{t|luy|dakitari}}\n* Luo: {{t|luo|dokta}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|лекар|m}}, {{t|mk|лекарка|f}}\n* Malagasy: {{t+|mg|dokotera}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|doktor}} {{q|Malaysia, Singapore}}, {{t+|ms|dokter}} {{q|Indonesia incl. Riau}}, {{t|ms|bomor}} {{q|Southern Thailand}}, {{t+|ms|tabib}} {{q|limited}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|tabib|m}}\n* Manchu: {{t|mnc|ᠣᡴᡨᠣᠰᡳ|tr=oktosi}}, {{t|mnc|ᡩᠠᡳᡶᡠ|tr=daifu}}\n* Mansi:\n*: Northern Mansi: {{t-check|mns-nor|ле̄ккар}} {{attention|mns-nor|